It might be useful to inform commentators below that Singapore scores very low on almost every accepted measure of democracy. No media or newspapers exist without the express permission of the government. There is NO FREE PRESS in Singapore. Public expressions of any anti government opinions are not just banned but criminalised. Punishments for trivial offences are harsh. The death penalty exists. Singapore is undeniably run efficiently, but only for those who unquestioningly accept all government planning, and are obedient to every government dictat. There is almost no opposition in Singapore. It is in all but name a fascist government. Its financial management is reliant upon elitist monetary and fiscal policies that are essentially a house of cards. At some point it will reach peak population, peak building and extremely unequal wealth distribution and the cards will collapse. It has a veneer of fairness but underneath it is the Monaco of the East. For the time being it is true that if you join into the illusion and are totally obedient to the regime, you might do quite well, as long as you never question anything. The problems arise when so many people crammed into such a tiny space begin to realise that they do not live in a Utopia, but a Dystopia masquerading as something different. This film is of course a PR exercise. If you want to visit Singapore and observe just the surface, you can be duped into thinking it is a marvellous example of a successful nation, but dig just a tiny bit below the surface and you will see that things are not quite so perfect. Some of the comments below are staggeringly naive.

FORWARD PLANNING has always been in Singapore's DNA.  I migrated overseas because I have a strong dislike for human learning through disciplinary systems but we should give credits where it's due.  Dr. LEE Kuan Yew, Founder of majority-chinese Singapore, merged with Malaysia (or Malaya then) as he was hedging his bet on Independence from the majority-Muslim Malaya against the British colony.  He then called Singapore a multicultural city and instituted English as 1st Language (and not our Mother Tongue whether you are Chinese, Malay or Indian) in order to mitigate racial unrest while surrounded by Muslim countries.  Dr. LEE also knew the island was blessed with very deep harbours and a strategic location to world trade.  The journey began with the world's busiest sea port; than one of the busiest air ports; created a powerhouse financial hub; kept up by transactional outsourcing for conglomerates; pushing through integrated resorts (think Marina Bay Sands); and built the largest off-shore LNG storage and transformation facility.   Drone delivery, urban commercial farming and large-scale wireless electricity transmission are almost akin to passe concepts as these prototypes are being put to production in other parts of the world. I believe the main reason why Singapore was able to achieve what we have today is due to us having a flawed democracy. Our opposition are in a small minority thus the ruling party can make long term plans (10 to 50 years) instead of planning only for the next election as they are not restrict by a 4 or 5 years term thus time is not wasted on political or policy U-turn. With this, our politicians can spend less time playing the "house of cards" game and focus on building the country for the good of the majority. The question now is we do not have any natural resources and we can't grow gold or oil thus the only resource we can accumulate is wealth. This have not sat well with the majority of the Singaporean as the wealth gap is getting bigger by the year and to accumulate more wealth means the government has to choose between the foreign corporate investing in Singapore or the its people. Many less privileges are being left behind by our fast moving society with no hope of catching up and in my humble opinion, our government have not done enough to help them. As a Singaporean myself i crave a true democracy but am also afraid true democracy may cause ourselves to self-destruct.
